# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fault-injection-defense
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Cryptography prior to the modern age was effectively synonymous with encryption, converting readable information (plaintext) to unintelligible nonsense text (ciphertext), which can only be read by reversing the process (decryption).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The sender of an encrypted (coded) message shares the decryption (decoding) technique only with the intended recipients to preclude access from adversaries.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The cryptography literature often uses the names "Alice" (or "A") for the sender, "Bob" (or "B") for the intended recipient, and "Eve" (or "E") for the eavesdropping adversary.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Since the development of rotor cipher machines in World War I and the advent of computers in World War II, cryptography methods have become increasingly complex and their applications more varied.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Modern cryptography is heavily based on mathematical theory and computer science practice; cryptographic algorithms are designed around computational hardness assumptions, making such algorithms hard to break in actual practice by any adversary.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] While it is theoretically possible to break into a well-designed system, it is infeasible in actual practice to do so.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Such schemes, if well designed, are therefore termed "computationally secure".
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Theoretical advances (e.g., improvements in integer factorization algorithms) and faster computing technology require these designs to be continually reevaluated and, if necessary, adapted.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Information-theoretically secure schemes that provably cannot be broken even with unlimited computing power, such as the one-time pad, are much more difficult to use in practice than the best theoretically breakable but computationally secure schemes.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The growth of cryptographic technology has raised a number of legal issues in the Information Age.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Cryptography's potential for use as a tool for espionage and sedition has led many governments to classify it as a weapon and to limit or even prohibit its use and export.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In some jurisdictions where the use of cryptography is legal, laws permit investigators to compel the disclosure of encryption keys for documents relevant to an investigation.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Cryptography also plays a major role in digital rights management and copyright infringement disputes with regard to digital media.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The first use of the term "cryptograph" (as opposed to "cryptogram") dates back to the 19th century – originating from "The Gold-Bug", a story by Edgar Allan Poe.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The etymology of the term goes back to the Greek language; it is formed by two constituents: "crypton" (hidden), and "grapho" (to write).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Until modern times, cryptography referred almost exclusively to "encryption", which is the process of converting ordinary information (called plaintext) into an unintelligible form (called ciphertext).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Decryption is the reverse, in other words, moving from the unintelligible ciphertext back to plaintext.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] A cipher (or cypher) is a pair of algorithms that carry out the encryption and the reversing decryption.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The detailed operation of a cipher is controlled both by the algorithm and, in each instance, by a "key".
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The key is a secret (ideally known only to the communicants), usually a string of characters (ideally short so it can be remembered by the user), which is needed to decrypt the ciphertext.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In formal mathematical terms, a "cryptosystem" is the ordered list of elements of finite possible plaintexts, finite possible cyphertexts, finite possible keys, and the encryption and decryption algorithms that correspond to each key.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Keys are important both formally and in actual practice, as ciphers without variable keys can be trivially broken with only the knowledge of the cipher used and are therefore useless (or even counter-productive) for most purposes.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Historically, ciphers were often used directly for encryption or decryption without additional procedures such as authentication or integrity checks.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] There are two main types of cryptosystems: symmetric and asymmetric.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In symmetric systems, the only ones known until the 1970s, the same secret key encrypts and decrypts a message.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Data manipulation in symmetric systems is significantly faster than in asymmetric systems.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Asymmetric systems use a "public key" to encrypt a message and a related "private key" to decrypt it.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The advantage of asymmetric systems is that the public key can be freely published, allowing parties to establish secure communication without having a shared secret key.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In practice, asymmetric systems are used to first exchange a secret key, and then secure communication proceeds via a more efficient symmetric system using that key.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Examples of asymmetric systems include Diffie–Hellman key exchange, RSA (Rivest–Shamir–Adleman), ECC (Elliptic Curve Cryptography), and Post-quantum cryptography.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Secure symmetric algorithms include the commonly used AES (Advanced Encryption Standard) which replaced the older DES (Data Encryption Standard).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Insecure symmetric algorithms include children's language tangling schemes such as Pig Latin or other cant, and all historical cryptographic schemes, however seriously intended, prior to the invention of the one-time pad early in the 20th century.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In colloquial use, the term "code" is often used to mean any method of encryption or concealment of meaning.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] However, in cryptography, code has a more specific meaning: the replacement of a unit of plaintext (i.e., a meaningful word or phrase) with a code word (for example, "wallaby" replaces "attack at dawn").
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] A cypher, in contrast, is a scheme for changing or substituting an element below such a level (a letter, a syllable, or a pair of letters, etc.) to produce a cyphertext.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Cryptanalysis is the term used for the study of methods for obtaining the meaning of encrypted information without access to the key normally required to do so; i.e., it is the study of how to "crack" encryption algorithms or their implementations.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] English is more flexible than several other languages in which "cryptology" (done by cryptologists) is always used in the second sense above.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] RFC 2828 advises that steganography is sometimes included in cryptology.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The study of characteristics of languages that have some application in cryptography or cryptology (e.g. frequency data, letter combinations, universal patterns, etc.) is called cryptolinguistics.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Cryptolingusitics is especially used in military intelligence applications for deciphering foreign communications.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Encryption attempted to ensure secrecy in communication, such as those of spies, military leaders, and diplomats.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In recent decades, the field has expanded beyond confidentiality concerns to include techniques for message integrity checking, sender/receiver identity authentication, digital signatures, interactive proofs and secure computation, among others.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Simple versions of either have never offered much confidentiality from enterprising opponents.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] An early substitution cipher was the Caesar cipher, in which each letter in the plaintext was replaced by a letter three positions further down the alphabet.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Suetonius reports that Julius Caesar used it with a shift of three to communicate with his generals.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Atbash is an example of an early Hebrew cipher.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The earliest known use of cryptography is some carved ciphertext on stone in Egypt (c.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] 1900 BCE), but this may have been done for the amusement of literate observers rather than as a way of concealing information.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The Greeks of Classical times are said to have known of ciphers (e.g., the scytale transposition cipher claimed to have been used by the Spartan military).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Steganography (i.e., hiding even the existence of a message so as to keep it confidential) was also first developed in ancient times.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] An early example, from Herodotus, was a message tattooed on a slave's shaved head and concealed under the regrown hair.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Other steganography methods involve 'hiding in plain sight,' such as using a music cipher to disguise an encrypted message within a regular piece of sheet music.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] More modern examples of steganography include the use of invisible ink, microdots, and digital watermarks to conceal information.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In India, the 2000-year-old *Kama Sutra* of Vātsyāyana speaks of two different kinds of ciphers called Kautiliyam and Mulavediya.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In the Kautiliyam, the cipher letter substitutions are based on phonetic relations, such as vowels becoming consonants.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In the Mulavediya, the cipher alphabet consists of pairing letters and using the reciprocal ones.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In Sassanid Persia, there were two secret scripts, according to the Muslim author Ibn al-Nadim: the *šāh-dabīrīya* (literally "King's script") which was used for official correspondence, and the *rāz-saharīya* which was used to communicate secret messages with other countries.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] David Kahn notes in *The Codebreakers* that modern cryptology originated among the Arabs, the first people to systematically document cryptanalytic methods.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Al-Khalil (717–786) wrote the *Book of Cryptographic Messages*, which contains the first use of permutations and combinations to list all possible Arabic words with and without vowels.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Ciphertexts produced by a classical cipher (and some modern ciphers) will reveal statistical information about the plaintext, and that information can often be used to break the cipher.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] After the discovery of frequency analysis, nearly all such ciphers could be broken by an informed attacker.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Such classical ciphers still enjoy popularity today, though mostly as puzzles (see cryptogram).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The Arab mathematician and polymath Al-Kindi wrote a book on cryptography entitled *Risalah fi Istikhraj al-Mu'amma* (*Manuscript for the Deciphering Cryptographic Messages*), which described the first known use of frequency analysis cryptanalysis techniques.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Language letter frequencies may offer little help for some extended historical encryption techniques such as homophonic cipher that tend to flatten the frequency distribution.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] For those ciphers, language letter group (or n-gram) frequencies may provide an attack.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Essentially all ciphers remained vulnerable to cryptanalysis using the frequency analysis technique until the development of the polyalphabetic cipher, most clearly by Leon Battista Alberti around the year 1467, though there is some indication that it was already known to Al-Kindi.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Alberti's innovation was to use different ciphers (i.e., substitution alphabets) for various parts of a message (perhaps for each successive plaintext letter at the limit).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] He also invented what was probably the first automatic cipher device, a wheel that implemented a partial realization of his invention.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In the Vigenère cipher, a polyalphabetic cipher, encryption uses a *key word*, which controls letter substitution depending on which letter of the key word is used.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In the mid-19th century Charles Babbage showed that the Vigenère cipher was vulnerable to Kasiski examination, but this was first published about ten years later by Friedrich Kasiski.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Although frequency analysis can be a powerful and general technique against many ciphers, encryption has still often been effective in practice, as many a would-be cryptanalyst was unaware of the technique.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Breaking a message without using frequency analysis essentially required knowledge of the cipher used and perhaps of the key involved, thus making espionage, bribery, burglary, defection, etc., more attractive approaches to the cryptanalytically uninformed.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Security of the key used should alone be sufficient for a good cipher to maintain confidentiality under an attack.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Different physical devices and aids have been used to assist with ciphers.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] One of the earliest may have been the scytale of ancient Greece, a rod supposedly used by the Spartans as an aid for a transposition cipher.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In medieval times, other aids were invented such as the cipher grille, which was also used for a kind of steganography.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] With the invention of polyalphabetic ciphers came more sophisticated aids such as Alberti's own cipher disk, Johannes Trithemius' tabula recta scheme, and Thomas Jefferson's wheel cypher (not publicly known, and reinvented independently by Bazeries around 1900).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Many mechanical encryption/decryption devices were invented early in the 20th century, and several patented, among them rotor machines—famously including the Enigma machine used by the German government and military from the late 1920s and during World War II.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The ciphers implemented by better quality examples of these machine designs brought about a substantial increase in cryptanalytic difficulty after WWI.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Cryptanalysis of the new mechanical ciphering devices proved to be both difficult and laborious.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In the United Kingdom, cryptanalytic efforts at Bletchley Park during WWII spurred the development of more efficient means for carrying out repetitive tasks, such as military code breaking (decryption).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] This culminated in the development of the Colossus, the world's first fully electronic, digital, programmable computer, which assisted in the decryption of ciphers generated by the German Army's Lorenz SZ40/42 machine.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Extensive open academic research into cryptography is relatively recent, beginning in the mid-1970s.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In the early 1970s IBM personnel designed the Data Encryption Standard (DES) algorithm that became the first federal government cryptography standard in the United States.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In 1976 Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman published the Diffie–Hellman key exchange algorithm.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In 1977 the RSA algorithm was published in Martin Gardner's *Scientific American* column.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Since then, cryptography has become a widely used tool in communications, computer networks, and computer security generally.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Some modern cryptographic techniques can only keep their keys secret if certain mathematical problems are intractable, such as the integer factorization or the discrete logarithm problems, so there are deep connections with abstract mathematics.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] There are very few cryptosystems that are proven to be unconditionally secure.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The one-time pad is one, and was proven to be so by Claude Shannon.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] There are a few important algorithms that have been proven secure under certain assumptions.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] For example, the infeasibility of factoring extremely large integers is the basis for believing that RSA is secure, and some other systems, but even so, proof of unbreakability is unavailable since the underlying mathematical problem remains open.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In practice, these are widely used, and are believed unbreakable in practice by most competent observers.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] There are systems similar to RSA, such as one by Michael O.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Rabin that are provably secure provided factoring *n = pq* is impossible; it is quite unusable in practice.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The discrete logarithm problem is the basis for believing some other cryptosystems are secure, and again, there are related, less practical systems that are provably secure relative to the solvability or insolvability discrete log problem.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] As well as being aware of cryptographic history, cryptographic algorithm and system designers must also sensibly consider probable future developments while working on their designs.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] For instance, continuous improvements in computer processing power have increased the scope of brute-force attacks, so when specifying key lengths, the required key lengths are similarly advancing.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The potential impact of quantum computing are already being considered by some cryptographic system designers developing post-quantum cryptography.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The announced imminence of small implementations of these machines may be making the need for preemptive caution rather more than merely speculative.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Claude Shannon's two papers, his 1948 paper on information theory, and especially his 1949 paper on cryptography, laid the foundations of modern cryptography and provided a mathematical basis for future cryptography.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] His 1949 paper has been noted as having provided a "solid theoretical basis for cryptography and for cryptanalysis", and as having turned cryptography from an "art to a science".
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] As a result of his contributions and work, he has been described as the "founding father of modern cryptography".
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Prior to the early 20th century, cryptography was mainly concerned with linguistic and lexicographic patterns.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Since then cryptography has broadened in scope, and now makes extensive use of mathematical subdisciplines, including information theory, computational complexity, statistics, combinatorics, abstract algebra, number theory, and finite mathematics.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Cryptography is also a branch of engineering, but an unusual one since it deals with active, intelligent, and malevolent opposition; other kinds of engineering (e.g., civil or chemical engineering) need deal only with neutral natural forces.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] There is also active research examining the relationship between cryptographic problems and quantum physics.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Just as the development of digital computers and electronics helped in cryptanalysis, it made possible much more complex ciphers.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Furthermore, computers allowed for the encryption of any kind of data representable in any binary format, unlike classical ciphers which only encrypted written language texts; this was new and significant.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Computer use has thus supplanted linguistic cryptography, both for cipher design and cryptanalysis.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Many computer ciphers can be characterized by their operation on binary bit sequences (sometimes in groups or blocks), unlike classical and mechanical schemes, which generally manipulate traditional characters (i.e., letters and digits) directly.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] However, computers have also assisted cryptanalysis, which has compensated to some extent for increased cipher complexity.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Research into **post-quantum cryptography** (PQC) has intensified because practical quantum computers would break widely deployed public-key systems such as RSA, Diffie–Hellman and ECC.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] A 2017 review in *Nature* surveys the leading PQC families—lattice-based, code-based, multivariate-quadratic and hash-based schemes—and stresses that standardisation and deployment should proceed well before large-scale quantum machines become available.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Symmetric-key cryptography refers to encryption methods in which both the sender and receiver share the same key (or, less commonly, in which their keys are different, but related in an easily computable way).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] This was the only kind of encryption publicly known until June 1976.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Symmetric key ciphers are implemented as either block ciphers or stream ciphers.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] A block cipher enciphers input in blocks of plaintext as opposed to individual characters, the input form used by a stream cipher.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The Data Encryption Standard (DES) and the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) are block cipher designs that have been designated cryptography standards by the US government (though DES's designation was finally withdrawn after the AES was adopted).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Despite its deprecation as an official standard, DES (especially its still-approved and much more secure triple-DES variant) remains quite popular; it is used across a wide range of applications, from ATM encryption to e-mail privacy and secure remote access.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Many other block ciphers have been designed and released, with considerable variation in quality.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Many, even some designed by capable practitioners, have been thoroughly broken, such as FEAL.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Stream ciphers, in contrast to the 'block' type, create an arbitrarily long stream of key material, which is combined with the plaintext bit-by-bit or character-by-character, somewhat like the one-time pad.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In a stream cipher, the output stream is created based on a hidden internal state that changes as the cipher operates.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] That internal state is initially set up using the secret key material.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Block ciphers can be used as stream ciphers by generating blocks of a keystream (in place of a Pseudorandom number generator) and applying an XOR operation to each bit of the plaintext with each bit of the keystream.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Message authentication codes (MACs) are much like cryptographic hash functions, except that a secret key can be used to authenticate the hash value upon receipt; this additional complication blocks an attack scheme against bare digest algorithms, and so has been thought worth the effort.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Cryptographic hash functions are a third type of cryptographic algorithm.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] They take a message of any length as input, and output a short, fixed-length hash, which can be used in (for example) a digital signature.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] For good hash functions, an attacker cannot find two messages that produce the same hash.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] MD4 is a long-used hash function that is now broken; MD5, a strengthened variant of MD4, is also widely used but broken in practice.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The competition ended on October 2, 2012, when the NIST announced that Keccak would be the new SHA-3 hash algorithm.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Unlike block and stream ciphers that are invertible, cryptographic hash functions produce a hashed output that cannot be used to retrieve the original input data.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Cryptographic hash functions are used to verify the authenticity of data retrieved from an untrusted source or to add a layer of security.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Symmetric-key cryptosystems use the same key for encryption and decryption of a message, although a message or group of messages can have a different key than others.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] A significant disadvantage of symmetric ciphers is the key management necessary to use them securely.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Each distinct pair of communicating parties must, ideally, share a different key, and perhaps for each ciphertext exchanged as well.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The number of keys required increases as the square of the number of network members, which very quickly requires complex key management schemes to keep them all consistent and secret.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In a groundbreaking 1976 paper, Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman proposed the notion of *public-key* (also, more generally, called *asymmetric key*) cryptography in which two different but mathematically related keys are used—a *public* key and a *private* key.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] A public key system is so constructed that calculation of one key (the 'private key') is computationally infeasible from the other (the 'public key'), even though they are necessarily related.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Instead, both keys are generated secretly, as an interrelated pair.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The historian David Kahn described public-key cryptography as "the most revolutionary new concept in the field since polyalphabetic substitution emerged in the Renaissance".
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In public-key cryptosystems, the public key may be freely distributed, while its paired private key must remain secret.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The *public key* is used for encryption, while the *private* or *secret key* is used for decryption.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] While Diffie and Hellman could not find such a system, they showed that public-key cryptography was indeed possible by presenting the Diffie–Hellman key exchange protocol, a solution that is now widely used in secure communications to allow two parties to secretly agree on a shared encryption key.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The X.509 standard defines the most commonly used format for public key certificates.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Diffie and Hellman's publication sparked widespread academic efforts in finding a practical public-key encryption system.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] This race was finally won in 1978 by Ronald Rivest, Adi Shamir, and Len Adleman, whose solution has since become known as the RSA algorithm.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The Diffie–Hellman and RSA algorithms, in addition to being the first publicly known examples of high-quality public-key algorithms, have been among the most widely used.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Other asymmetric-key algorithms include the Cramer–Shoup cryptosystem, ElGamal encryption, and various elliptic curve techniques.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] A document published in 1997 by the Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), a British intelligence organization, revealed that cryptographers at GCHQ had anticipated several academic developments.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Ellis had conceived the principles of asymmetric key cryptography.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In 1973, Clifford Cocks invented a solution that was very similar in design rationale to RSA.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Williamson is claimed to have developed the Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Public-key cryptography is also used for implementing digital signature schemes.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] A digital signature is reminiscent of an ordinary signature; they both have the characteristic of being easy for a user to produce, but difficult for anyone else to forge.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Digital signatures can also be permanently tied to the content of the message being signed; they cannot then be 'moved' from one document to another, for any attempt will be detectable.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In digital signature schemes, there are two algorithms: one for *signing*, in which a secret key is used to process the message (or a hash of the message, or both), and one for *verification*, in which the matching public key is used with the message to check the validity of the signature.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] RSA and DSA are two of the most popular digital signature schemes.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Digital signatures are central to the operation of public key infrastructures and many network security schemes (e.g., SSL/TLS, many VPNs, etc.).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Public-key algorithms are most often based on the computational complexity of "hard" problems, often from number theory.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] For example, the hardness of RSA is related to the integer factorization problem, while Diffie–Hellman and DSA are related to the discrete logarithm problem.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The security of elliptic curve cryptography is based on number theoretic problems involving elliptic curves.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Because of the difficulty of the underlying problems, most public-key algorithms involve operations such as modular multiplication and exponentiation, which are much more computationally expensive than the techniques used in most block ciphers, especially with typical key sizes.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] As a result, public-key cryptosystems are commonly hybrid cryptosystems, in which a fast high-quality symmetric-key encryption algorithm is used for the message itself, while the relevant symmetric key is sent with the message, but encrypted using a public-key algorithm.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Similarly, hybrid signature schemes are often used, in which a cryptographic hash function is computed, and only the resulting hash is digitally signed.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Cryptographic hash functions are functions that take a variable-length input and return a fixed-length output, which can be used in, for example, a digital signature.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] For a hash function to be secure, it must be difficult to compute two inputs that hash to the same value (collision resistance) and to compute an input that hashes to a given output (preimage resistance).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The goal of cryptanalysis is to find some weakness or insecurity in a cryptographic scheme, thus permitting its subversion or evasion.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] It is a common misconception that every encryption method can be broken.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In connection with his WWII work at Bell Labs, Claude Shannon proved that the one-time pad cipher is unbreakable, provided the key material is truly random, never reused, kept secret from all possible attackers, and of equal or greater length than the message.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Most ciphers, apart from the one-time pad, can be broken with enough computational effort by brute force attack, but the amount of effort needed may be exponentially dependent on the key size, as compared to the effort needed to make use of the cipher.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In such cases, effective security could be achieved if it is proven that the effort required (i.e., "work factor", in Shannon's terms) is beyond the ability of any adversary.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] This means it must be shown that no efficient method (as opposed to the time-consuming brute force method) can be found to break the cipher.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Since no such proof has been found to date, the one-time-pad remains the only theoretically unbreakable cipher.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Although well-implemented one-time-pad encryption cannot be broken, traffic analysis is still possible.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] There are a wide variety of cryptanalytic attacks, and they can be classified in any of several ways.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] A common distinction turns on what Eve (an attacker) knows and what capabilities are available.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In a ciphertext-only attack, Eve has access only to the ciphertext (good modern cryptosystems are usually effectively immune to ciphertext-only attacks).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In a known-plaintext attack, Eve has access to a ciphertext and its corresponding plaintext (or to many such pairs).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In a chosen-plaintext attack, Eve may choose a plaintext and learn its corresponding ciphertext (perhaps many times); an example is gardening, used by the British during WWII.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In a chosen-ciphertext attack, Eve may be able to *choose* ciphertexts and learn their corresponding plaintexts.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Finally in a man-in-the-middle attack Eve gets in between Alice (the sender) and Bob (the recipient), accesses and modifies the traffic and then forward it to the recipient.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Also important, often overwhelmingly so, are mistakes (generally in the design or use of one of the protocols involved).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Cryptanalysis of symmetric-key ciphers typically involves looking for attacks against the block ciphers or stream ciphers that are more efficient than any attack that could be against a perfect cipher.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] For example, a simple brute force attack against DES requires one known plaintext and 255 decryptions, trying approximately half of the possible keys, to reach a point at which chances are better than even that the key sought will have been found.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] But this may not be enough assurance; a linear cryptanalysis attack against DES requires 243 known plaintexts (with their corresponding ciphertexts) and approximately 243 DES operations.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] This is a considerable improvement over brute force attacks.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Public-key algorithms are based on the computational difficulty of various problems.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The most famous of these are the difficulty of integer factorization of semiprimes and the difficulty of calculating discrete logarithms, both of which are not yet proven to be solvable in polynomial time (**P**) using only a classical Turing-complete computer.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Much public-key cryptanalysis concerns designing algorithms in **P** that can solve these problems, or using other technologies, such as quantum computers.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] For instance, the best-known algorithms for solving the elliptic curve-based version of discrete logarithm are much more time-consuming than the best-known algorithms for factoring, at least for problems of more or less equivalent size.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Thus, to achieve an equivalent strength of encryption, techniques that depend upon the difficulty of factoring large composite numbers, such as the RSA cryptosystem, require larger keys than elliptic curve techniques.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] For this reason, public-key cryptosystems based on elliptic curves have become popular since their invention in the mid-1990s.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] While pure cryptanalysis uses weaknesses in the algorithms themselves, other attacks on cryptosystems are based on actual use of the algorithms in real devices, and are called *side-channel attacks*.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] If a cryptanalyst has access to, for example, the amount of time the device took to encrypt a number of plaintexts or report an error in a password or PIN character, they may be able to use a timing attack to break a cipher that is otherwise resistant to analysis.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] An attacker might also study the pattern and length of messages to derive valuable information; this is known as traffic analysis and can be quite useful to an alert adversary.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Poor administration of a cryptosystem, such as permitting too short keys, will make any system vulnerable, regardless of other virtues.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Social engineering and other attacks against humans (e.g., bribery, extortion, blackmail, espionage, rubber-hose cryptanalysis or torture) are usually employed due to being more cost-effective and feasible to perform in a reasonable amount of time compared to pure cryptanalysis by a high margin.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Much of the theoretical work in cryptography concerns cryptographic *primitives*—algorithms with basic cryptographic properties—and their relationship to other cryptographic problems.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] More complicated cryptographic tools are then built from these basic primitives.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] These primitives provide fundamental properties, which are used to develop more complex tools called *cryptosystems* or *cryptographic protocols*, which guarantee one or more high-level security properties.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Note, however, that the distinction between cryptographic *primitives* and cryptosystems, is quite arbitrary; for example, the RSA algorithm is sometimes considered a cryptosystem, and sometimes a primitive.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Typical examples of cryptographic primitives include pseudorandom functions, one-way functions, etc.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] One or more cryptographic primitives are often used to develop a more complex algorithm, called a cryptographic system, or *cryptosystem*.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Cryptosystems (e.g., El-Gamal encryption) are designed to provide particular functionality (e.g., public key encryption) while guaranteeing certain security properties (e.g., chosen-plaintext attack (CPA) security in the random oracle model).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Cryptosystems use the properties of the underlying cryptographic primitives to support the system's security properties.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] As the distinction between primitives and cryptosystems is somewhat arbitrary, a sophisticated cryptosystem can be derived from a combination of several more primitive cryptosystems.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In many cases, the cryptosystem's structure involves back and forth communication among two or more parties in space (e.g., between the sender of a secure message and its receiver) or across time (e.g., cryptographically protected backup data).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Such cryptosystems are sometimes called *cryptographic protocols*.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Some widely known cryptosystems include RSA, Schnorr signature, ElGamal encryption, and Pretty Good Privacy (PGP).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] More complex cryptosystems include electronic cash systems, signcryption systems, etc.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Some more 'theoretical' cryptosystems include interactive proof systems, (like zero-knowledge proofs) and systems for secret sharing.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Lightweight cryptography (LWC) concerns cryptographic algorithms developed for a strictly constrained environment.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The growth of Internet of Things (IoT) has spiked research into the development of lightweight algorithms that are better suited for the environment.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] An IoT environment requires strict constraints on power consumption, processing power, and security.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Algorithms such as Ascon and SPECK are examples of the many LWC algorithms that have been developed to match the criteria for the CAESAR Competition and the standard set by the National Institute of Standards and Technology.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Cryptography is widely used on the internet to help protect user-data and prevent eavesdropping.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] To ensure secrecy during transmission, many systems use private key cryptography to protect transmitted information.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] With public-key systems, one can maintain secrecy without a master key or a large number of keys.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] But, some algorithms like BitLocker and VeraCrypt are generally not private-public key cryptography.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] For example, Veracrypt uses a password hash to generate the single private key.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] However, it can be configured to run in public-private key systems.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The C++ opensource encryption library OpenSSL provides free and opensource encryption software and tools.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] The most commonly used encryption cipher suit is AES, as it has hardware acceleration for all x86 based processors that has AES-NI.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] A close contender is ChaCha20-Poly1305, which is a stream cipher, however it is commonly used for mobile devices as they are ARM based which does not feature AES-NI instruction set extension.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Cryptography can be used to secure communications by encrypting them.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] "End-to-end" encryption, where only sender and receiver can read messages, is implemented for email in Pretty Good Privacy and for secure messaging in general in WhatsApp, Signal and Telegram.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Operating systems use encryption to keep passwords secret, conceal parts of the system, and ensure that software updates are truly from the system maker.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Instead of storing plaintext passwords, computer systems store hashes thereof; then, when a user logs in, the system passes the given password through a cryptographic hash function and compares it to the hashed value on file.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] In this manner, neither the system nor an attacker has at any point access to the password in plaintext.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Encryption is sometimes used to encrypt one's entire drive.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] For example, University College London has implemented BitLocker (a program by Microsoft) to render drive data opaque without users logging in.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Cryptographic techniques enable cryptocurrency technologies, such as distributed ledger technologies (e.g., blockchains), which finance cryptoeconomics applications such as decentralized finance (DeFi).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Key cryptographic techniques that enable cryptocurrencies and cryptoeconomics include, but are not limited to: cryptographic keys, cryptographic hash function, asymmetric (public key) encryption, Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA), End-to-End Encryption (E2EE), and Zero Knowledge Proofs (ZKP).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] Estimates suggest that a quantum computer could reduce the effort required to break today’s strongest RSA or elliptic-curve keys from millennia to mere seconds, rendering current protocols (such as the versions of TLS that rely on those keys) insecure.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p01] To mitigate this "quantum threat", researchers are developing quantum-resistant algorithms whose security rests on problems believed to remain hard for both classical and quantum computers.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Cryptography has long been of interest to intelligence gathering and law enforcement agencies.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Secret communications may be criminal or even treasonous.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Because of its facilitation of privacy, and the diminution of privacy attendant on its prohibition, cryptography is also of considerable interest to civil rights supporters.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Accordingly, there has been a history of controversial legal issues surrounding cryptography, especially since the advent of inexpensive computers has made widespread access to high-quality cryptography possible.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] In some countries, even the domestic use of cryptography is, or has been, restricted.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Until 1999, France significantly restricted the use of cryptography domestically, though it has since relaxed many of these rules.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] In China and Iran, a license is still required to use cryptography.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Many countries have tight restrictions on the use of cryptography.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Among the more restrictive are laws in Belarus, Kazakhstan, Mongolia, Pakistan, Singapore, Tunisia, and Vietnam.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] In the United States, cryptography is legal for domestic use, but there has been much conflict over legal issues related to cryptography.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] One particularly important issue has been the export of cryptography and cryptographic software and hardware.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Probably because of the importance of cryptanalysis in World War II and an expectation that cryptography would continue to be important for national security, many Western governments have, at some point, strictly regulated export of cryptography.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] After World War II, it was illegal in the US to sell or distribute encryption technology overseas; in fact, encryption was designated as auxiliary military equipment and put on the United States Munitions List.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Until the development of the personal computer, asymmetric key algorithms (i.e., public key techniques), and the Internet, this was not especially problematic.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] However, as the Internet grew and computers became more widely available, high-quality encryption techniques became well known around the globe.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] In the 1990s, there were several challenges to US export regulation of cryptography.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Bernstein, then a graduate student at UC Berkeley, brought a lawsuit against the US government challenging some aspects of the restrictions based on free speech grounds.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] United States* ultimately resulted in a 1999 decision that printed source code for cryptographic algorithms and systems was protected as free speech by the United States Constitution.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] In 1996, thirty-nine countries signed the Wassenaar Arrangement, an arms control treaty that deals with the export of arms and "dual-use" technologies such as cryptography.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] The treaty stipulated that the use of cryptography with short key-lengths (56-bit for symmetric encryption, 512-bit for RSA) would no longer be export-controlled.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Cryptography exports from the US became less strictly regulated as a consequence of a major relaxation in 2000; there are no longer very many restrictions on key sizes in US-exported mass-market software.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] The Mozilla Thunderbird and Microsoft Outlook E-mail client programs similarly can transmit and receive emails via TLS, and can send and receive email encrypted with S/MIME.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Many Internet users do not realize that their basic application software contains such extensive cryptosystems.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Another contentious issue connected to cryptography in the United States is the influence of the National Security Agency on cipher development and policy.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] The NSA was involved with the design of DES during its development at IBM and its consideration by the National Bureau of Standards as a possible Federal Standard for cryptography.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] DES was designed to be resistant to differential cryptanalysis, a powerful and general cryptanalytic technique known to the NSA and IBM, that became publicly known only when it was rediscovered in the late 1980s.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] According to Steven Levy, IBM discovered differential cryptanalysis, but kept the technique secret at the NSA's request.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] The technique became publicly known only when Biham and Shamir re-discovered and announced it some years later.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] The entire affair illustrates the difficulty of determining what resources and knowledge an attacker might actually have.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Another instance of the NSA's involvement was the 1993 Clipper chip affair, an encryption microchip intended to be part of the Capstone cryptography-control initiative.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Clipper was widely criticized by cryptographers for two reasons.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] The cipher algorithm (called Skipjack) was then classified (declassified in 1998, long after the Clipper initiative lapsed).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] The classified cipher caused concerns that the NSA had deliberately made the cipher weak to assist its intelligence efforts.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] The whole initiative was also criticized based on its violation of Kerckhoffs's Principle, as the scheme included a special escrow key held by the government for use by law enforcement (i.e. wiretapping).
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Cryptography is central to digital rights management (DRM), a group of techniques for technologically controlling use of copyrighted material, being widely implemented and deployed at the behest of some copyright holders.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] President Bill Clinton signed the Digital Millennium Copyright Act (DMCA), which criminalized all production, dissemination, and use of certain cryptanalytic techniques and technology (now known or later discovered); specifically, those that could be used to circumvent DRM technological schemes.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] This had a noticeable impact on the cryptography research community since an argument can be made that any cryptanalytic research violated the DMCA.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Similar statutes have since been enacted in several countries and regions, including the implementation in the EU Copyright Directive.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Similar restrictions are called for by treaties signed by World Intellectual Property Organization member-states.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] The United States Department of Justice and FBI have not enforced the DMCA as rigorously as had been feared by some, but the law, nonetheless, remains a controversial one.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Niels Ferguson, a well-respected cryptography researcher, has publicly stated that he will not release some of his research into an Intel security design for fear of prosecution under the DMCA.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Cryptologist Bruce Schneier has argued that the DMCA encourages vendor lock-in, while inhibiting actual measures toward cyber-security.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Both Alan Cox (longtime Linux kernel developer) and Edward Felten (and some of his students at Princeton) have encountered problems related to the Act.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Dmitry Sklyarov was arrested during a visit to the US from Russia, and jailed for five months pending trial for alleged violations of the DMCA arising from work he had done in Russia, where the work was legal.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] In 2007, the cryptographic keys responsible for Blu-ray and HD DVD content scrambling were discovered and released onto the Internet.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] In both cases, the Motion Picture Association of America sent out numerous DMCA takedown notices, and there was a massive Internet backlash triggered by the perceived impact of such notices on fair use and free speech.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] In the United Kingdom, the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act gives UK police the powers to force suspects to decrypt files or hand over passwords that protect encryption keys.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Failure to comply is an offense in its own right, punishable on conviction by a two-year jail sentence or up to five years in cases involving national security.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Successful prosecutions have occurred under the Act; the first, in 2009, resulted in a term of 13 months' imprisonment.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Similar forced disclosure laws in Australia, Finland, France, and India compel individual suspects under investigation to hand over encryption keys or passwords during a criminal investigation.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] In the United States, the federal criminal case of *United States v.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] Fricosu* addressed whether a search warrant can compel a person to reveal an encryption passphrase or password.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] The Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF) argued that this is a violation of the protection from self-incrimination given by the Fifth Amendment.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] In 2012, the court ruled that under the All Writs Act, the defendant was required to produce an unencrypted hard drive for the court.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] In many jurisdictions, the legal status of forced disclosure remains unclear.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] The 2016 FBI–Apple encryption dispute concerns the ability of courts in the United States to compel manufacturers' assistance in unlocking cell phones whose contents are cryptographically protected.
[src:fault-injection-defense/cryptography-p02] As a potential counter-measure to forced disclosure some cryptographic software supports plausible deniability, where the encrypted data is indistinguishable from unused random data (for example such as that of a drive which has been securely wiped).
[src:fault-injection-defense/differential-fault-analysis] When stressed like this, the processor may begin to output incorrect results due to physical data corruption, which may help a cryptanalyst deduce the instructions that the processor is running, or what the internal state of its data is.
[src:fault-injection-defense/differential-fault-analysis] For DES and Triple DES, about 200 single-flipped bits are necessary to obtain a secret key.
[src:fault-injection-defense/differential-fault-analysis] DFA has also been applied successfully to the AES cipher.
[src:fault-injection-defense/differential-fault-analysis] Many countermeasures have been proposed to defend from these kinds of attacks.
[src:fault-injection-defense/differential-fault-analysis] Most of them are based on error detection schemes.
[src:fault-injection-defense/differential-fault-analysis] A fault injection attack involves stressing the transistors responsible for encryption tasks to generate faults that will then be used as input for analysis.
[src:fault-injection-defense/differential-fault-analysis] The stress can be an electromagnetic pulse (EM pulse or laser pulse).
[src:fault-injection-defense/differential-fault-analysis] Practical fault injection consists of using an electromagnetic probe connected to a pulser or a laser generating a disturbance of a similar length to the processor's cycle time (of the order of a nanosecond).
[src:fault-injection-defense/differential-fault-analysis] The energy transferred to the chip may be sufficient to burn out certain components of the chip, so the voltage of the pulser (a few hundred volts) and the positioning of the probe must be finely calibrated.
[src:fault-injection-defense/differential-fault-analysis] For greater precision, the chips are often decapsulated (chemically eroded to expose the bare silicon).
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] In information theory and coding theory with applications in computer science and telecommunications, **error detection and correction** (**EDAC**) or **error control** are techniques that enable reliable delivery of digital data over unreliable communication channels.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Many communication channels are subject to channel noise, and thus errors may be introduced during transmission from the source to a receiver.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Error detection techniques allow detecting such errors, while error correction enables reconstruction of the original data in many cases.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] In classical antiquity, copyists of the Hebrew Bible were paid for their work according to the number of stichs (lines of verse).
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] As the prose books of the Bible were hardly ever written in stichs, the copyists, in order to estimate the amount of work, had to count the letters.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] This also helped ensure accuracy in the transmission of the text with the production of subsequent copies.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Between the 7th and 10th centuries CE a group of Jewish scribes formalized and expanded this to create the Numerical Masorah to ensure accurate reproduction of the sacred text.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] It included counts of the number of words in a line, section, book and groups of books, noting the middle stich of a book, word use statistics, and commentary.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Standards became such that a deviation in even a single letter in a Torah scroll was considered unacceptable.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The effectiveness of their error correction method was verified by the accuracy of copying through the centuries demonstrated by discovery of the Dead Sea Scrolls in 1947–1956, dating from c.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The modern development of error correction codes is credited to Richard Hamming in 1947.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] A description of Hamming's code appeared in Claude Shannon's *A Mathematical Theory of Communication* and was quickly generalized by Marcel J.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] All error-detection and correction schemes add some redundancy (i.e., some extra data) to a message, which receivers can use to check consistency of the delivered message and to recover data that has been determined to be corrupted.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Error detection and correction schemes can be either systematic or non-systematic.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] In a systematic scheme, the transmitter sends the original (error-free) data and attaches a fixed number of *check bits* (or *parity data*), which are derived from the data bits by some encoding algorithm.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] If error detection is required, a receiver can simply apply the same algorithm to the received data bits and compare its output with the received check bits; if the values do not match, an error has occurred at some point during the transmission.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] If error correction is required, a receiver can apply the decoding algorithm to the received data bits and the received check bits to recover the original error-free data.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] In a system that uses a non-systematic code, the original message is transformed into an encoded message carrying the same information, and that has at least as many bits as the original message.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Good error control performance requires the scheme to be selected based on the characteristics of the communication channel.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Common channel models include memoryless models where errors occur randomly and with a certain probability, and dynamic models where errors occur primarily in bursts.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Consequently, error-detecting and -correcting codes can be generally distinguished between *random-error-detecting/correcting* and *burst-error-detecting/correcting*.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Some codes can also be suitable for a mixture of random errors and burst errors.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] If the channel characteristics cannot be determined or are highly variable, an error-detection scheme may be combined with a system for retransmission of erroneous data.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] This is known as automatic repeat request (ARQ), and is most notably used on the Internet.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] An alternate approach for error control is hybrid automatic repeat request (HARQ), which is a combination of ARQ and error-correction coding.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Automatic repeat request (ARQ) is an error control method for data transmission that makes use of error-detection codes, acknowledgment and/or negative acknowledgment messages, and timeouts to achieve reliable data transmission.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] An *acknowledgment* is a message sent by the receiver to indicate that it has correctly received a data frame.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Usually, when the transmitter does not receive the acknowledgment before the timeout occurs (i.e., within a reasonable amount of time after sending the data frame), it retransmits the frame until it is either correctly received or the error persists beyond a predetermined number of retransmissions.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Three types of ARQ protocols are Stop-and-wait ARQ, Go-Back-N ARQ, and Selective Repeat ARQ.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] ARQ is appropriate if the communication channel has varying or unknown capacity, such as is the case on the Internet.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] However, ARQ requires the availability of a back channel, results in possibly increased latency due to retransmissions, and requires the maintenance of buffers and timers for retransmissions, which in the case of network congestion can put a strain on the server and overall network capacity.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] For example, ARQ is used on shortwave radio data links in the form of ARQ-E, or combined with multiplexing as ARQ-M.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Since the receiver does not have to ask the sender for retransmission of the data, a backchannel is not required in forward error correction.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Error-correcting codes are used in lower-layer communication such as cellular network, high-speed fiber-optic communication and Wi-Fi, as well as for reliable storage in media such as flash memory, hard disk and RAM.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Shannon's theorem is an important theorem in forward error correction, and describes the maximum information rate at which reliable communication is possible over a channel that has a certain error probability or signal-to-noise ratio (SNR).
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] This strict upper limit is expressed in terms of the channel capacity.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] More specifically, the theorem says that there exist codes such that with increasing encoding length the probability of error on a discrete memoryless channel can be made arbitrarily small, provided that the code rate is lower than the channel capacity.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The code rate is defined as the fraction *k/n* of *k* source symbols and *n* encoded symbols.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The actual maximum code rate allowed depends on the error-correcting code used, and may be lower.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] This is because Shannon's proof was only of existential nature, and did not show how to construct codes that are both optimal and have efficient encoding and decoding algorithms.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Hybrid ARQ is a combination of ARQ and forward error correction.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The latter approach is particularly attractive on an erasure channel when using a rateless erasure code.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Error detection is most commonly realized using a suitable hash function (or specifically, a checksum, cyclic redundancy check or other algorithm).
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] A hash function adds a fixed-length *tag* to a message, which enables receivers to verify the delivered message by recomputing the tag and comparing it with the one provided.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] There exists a vast variety of different hash function designs.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] However, some are of particularly widespread use because of either their simplicity or their suitability for detecting certain kinds of errors (e.g., the cyclic redundancy check's performance in detecting burst errors).
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] A random-error-correcting code based on minimum distance coding can provide a strict guarantee on the number of detectable errors, but it may not protect against a preimage attack.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] A repetition code is a coding scheme that repeats the bits across a channel to achieve error-free communication.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Given a stream of data to be transmitted, the data are divided into blocks of bits.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Each block is transmitted some predetermined number of times.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] For example, to send the bit pattern 1011, the four-bit block can be repeated three times, thus producing 1011 1011 1011.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] If this twelve-bit pattern was received as 1010 1011 1011 – where the first block is unlike the other two – an error has occurred.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] A repetition code is very inefficient and can be susceptible to problems if the error occurs in exactly the same place for each group (e.g., 1010 1010 1010 in the previous example would be detected as correct).
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The advantage of repetition codes is that they are extremely simple, and are in fact used in some transmissions of numbers stations.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] A *parity bit* is a bit that is added to a group of source bits to ensure that the number of set bits (i.e., bits with value 1) in the outcome is even or odd.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] It is a very simple scheme that can be used to detect single or any other odd number (i.e., three, five, etc.) of errors in the output.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] An even number of flipped bits will make the parity bit appear correct even though the data is erroneous.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Parity bits added to each *word* sent are called transverse redundancy checks, while those added at the end of a stream of *words* are called longitudinal redundancy checks.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] For example, if each of a series of m-bit *words* has a parity bit added, showing whether there were an odd or even number of ones in that word, any word with a single error in it will be detected.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] It will not be known where in the word the error is, however.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] If, in addition, after each stream of n words a parity sum is sent, each bit of which shows whether there were an odd or even number of ones at that bit-position sent in the most recent group, the exact position of the error can be determined and the error corrected.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] This method is only guaranteed to be effective, however, if there are no more than 1 error in every group of n words.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] With more error correction bits, more errors can be detected and, in some cases, corrected.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] There are also other bit-grouping techniques.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] A *checksum* of a message is a modular arithmetic sum of message code words of a fixed word length (e.g., byte values).
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The sum may be negated by means of a ones'-complement operation prior to transmission to detect unintentional all-zero messages.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Checksum schemes include parity bits, check digits, and longitudinal redundancy checks.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Some checksum schemes, such as the Damm algorithm, the Luhn algorithm, and the Verhoeff algorithm, are specifically designed to detect errors commonly introduced by humans in writing down or remembering identification numbers.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] A *cyclic redundancy check* (CRC) is a non-secure hash function designed to detect accidental changes to digital data in computer networks.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] It is not suitable for detecting maliciously introduced errors.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] It is characterized by specification of a *generator polynomial*, which is used as the divisor in a polynomial long division over a finite field, taking the input data as the dividend.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] A CRC has properties that make it well suited for detecting burst errors.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] CRCs are particularly easy to implement in hardware and are therefore commonly used in computer networks and storage devices such as hard disk drives.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The parity bit can be seen as a special-case 1-bit CRC.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The output of a *cryptographic hash function*, also known as a *message digest*, can provide strong assurances about data integrity, whether changes of the data are accidental (e.g., due to transmission errors) or maliciously introduced.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Any modification to the data will likely be detected through a mismatching hash value.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Furthermore, given some hash value, it is typically infeasible to find some input data (other than the one given) that will yield the same hash value.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] If an attacker can change not only the message but also the hash value, then a *keyed hash* or message authentication code (MAC) can be used for additional security.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Without knowing the key, it is not possible for the attacker to easily or conveniently calculate the correct keyed hash value for a modified message.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Digital signatures can provide strong assurances about data integrity, whether the changes of the data are accidental or maliciously introduced.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Digital signatures are perhaps most notable for being part of the HTTPS protocol for securely browsing the web.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Any error-correcting code can be used for error detection.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] A code with *minimum Hamming distance*, *d*, can detect up to *d* − 1 errors in a code word.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Using minimum-distance-based error-correcting codes for error detection can be suitable if a strict limit on the minimum number of errors to be detected is desired.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Codes with minimum Hamming distance *d* = 2 are degenerate cases of error-correcting codes and can be used to detect single errors.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The parity bit is an example of a single-error-detecting code.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Applications that require low latency (such as telephone conversations) cannot use automatic repeat request (ARQ); they must use forward error correction (FEC).
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] By the time an ARQ system discovers an error and re-transmits it, the re-sent data will arrive too late to be usable.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Applications where the transmitter immediately forgets the information as soon as it is sent (such as most television cameras) cannot use ARQ; they must use FEC because when an error occurs, the original data is no longer available.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Applications that use ARQ must have a return channel; applications having no return channel cannot use ARQ.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Applications that require extremely low error rates (such as digital money transfers) must use ARQ due to the possibility of uncorrectable errors with FEC.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Reliability and inspection engineering also make use of the theory of error-correcting codes, as well as natural language.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The development of error-correction codes was tightly coupled with the history of deep-space missions due to the extreme dilution of signal power over interplanetary distances and the limited power availability aboard space probes.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Whereas early missions sent their data uncoded, starting in 1968, digital error correction was implemented in the form of (sub-optimally decoded) convolutional codes and Reed–Muller codes.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The Reed–Muller code was well suited to the noise the spacecraft was subject to (approximately matching a bell curve), and was implemented for the Mariner spacecraft and used on missions between 1969 and 1977.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The Voyager 1 and Voyager 2 missions, which started in 1977, were designed to deliver color imaging and scientific information from Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] This resulted in increased coding requirements, and thus, the spacecraft were supported by (optimally Viterbi-decoded) convolutional codes that could be concatenated with an outer Golay (24,12,8) code.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The Voyager 2 craft additionally supported an implementation of a Reed–Solomon code.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The concatenated Reed–Solomon–Viterbi (RSV) code allowed for very powerful error correction, and enabled the spacecraft's extended journey to Uranus and Neptune.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] After ECC system upgrades in 1989, both crafts used V2 RSV coding.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The Consultative Committee for Space Data Systems currently recommends usage of error correction codes with performance similar to the Voyager 2 RSV code as a minimum.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Concatenated codes are increasingly falling out of favor with space missions, and are replaced by more powerful codes such as Turbo codes or LDPC codes.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The different kinds of deep space and orbital missions that are conducted suggest that trying to find a one-size-fits-all error correction system will be an ongoing problem.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] For missions close to Earth, the nature of the noise in the communication channel is different from that which a spacecraft on an interplanetary mission experiences.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Additionally, as a spacecraft increases its distance from Earth, the problem of correcting for noise becomes more difficult.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The demand for satellite transponder bandwidth continues to grow, fueled by the desire to deliver television (including new channels and high-definition television) and IP data.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Transponder availability and bandwidth constraints have limited this growth.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Transponder capacity is determined by the selected modulation scheme and the proportion of capacity consumed by FEC.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Error detection and correction codes are often used to improve the reliability of data storage media.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] A parity track capable of detecting single-bit errors was present on the first magnetic tape data storage in 1951.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The optimal rectangular code used in group coded recording tapes not only detects but also corrects single-bit errors.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Some file formats, particularly archive formats, include a checksum (most often CRC-32]) to detect corruption and truncation and can employ redundancy or parity files to recover portions of corrupted data.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Reed-Solomon codes are used in compact discs to correct errors caused by scratches.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Modern hard drives use Reed–Solomon codes to detect and correct minor errors in sector reads, and to recover corrupted data from failing sectors and store that data in the spare sectors.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] RAID systems use a variety of error correction techniques to recover data when a hard drive completely fails.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Filesystems such as ZFS or Btrfs, as well as some RAID implementations, support data scrubbing and resilvering, which allows bad blocks to be detected and (hopefully) recovered before they are used.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] The recovered data may be re-written to exactly the same physical location, to spare blocks elsewhere on the same piece of hardware, or the data may be rewritten onto replacement hardware.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Dynamic random-access memory (DRAM) may provide stronger protection against soft errors by relying on error-correcting codes.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Such error-correcting memory, known as *ECC* or *EDAC-protected* memory, is particularly desirable for mission-critical applications, such as scientific computing, financial, medical, etc. as well as extraterrestrial applications due to the increased radiation in space.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Error-correcting memory controllers traditionally use Hamming codes, although some use triple modular redundancy.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] Interleaving allows distributing the effect of a single cosmic ray potentially upsetting multiple physically neighboring bits across multiple words by associating neighboring bits to different words.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] As long as a single-event upset (SEU) does not exceed the error threshold (e.g., a single error) in any particular word between accesses, it can be corrected (e.g., by a single-bit error-correcting code), and the illusion of an error-free memory system may be maintained.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] In addition to hardware providing features required for ECC memory to operate, operating systems usually contain related reporting facilities that are used to provide notifications when soft errors are transparently recovered.
[src:fault-injection-defense/error-detection-and-correction] A few systems also support memory scrubbing to catch and correct errors early before they become unrecoverable.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] In computer science, **fault injection** is a testing technique for understanding how computing systems behave when stressed in unusual ways.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] This can be achieved using physical- or software-based means, or using a hybrid approach.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Widely studied physical fault injections include the application of high voltages, extreme temperatures and electromagnetic pulses on electronic components, such as computer memory and central processing units.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] By exposing components to conditions beyond their intended operating limits, computing systems can be coerced into mis-executing instructions and corrupting critical data.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] In software testing, fault injection is a technique for improving the coverage of a test by introducing faults to test code paths; in particular error handling code paths, that might otherwise rarely be followed.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] It is often used with stress testing and is widely considered to be an important part of developing robust software.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Robustness testing (also known as syntax testing, fuzzing or fuzz testing) is a type of fault injection commonly used to test for vulnerabilities in communication interfaces such as protocols, command line parameters, or APIs.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] The propagation of a fault through to an observable failure follows a well-defined cycle.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] When executed, a fault may cause an error, which is an invalid state within a system boundary.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] An error may cause further errors within the system boundary, therefore each new error acts as a fault, or it may propagate to the system boundary and be observable.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] When error states are observed at the system boundary they are termed failures.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] This mechanism is termed the fault-error-failure cycle and is a key mechanism in dependability.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] The technique of fault injection dates back to the 1970s when it was first used to induce faults at a hardware level.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] This type of fault injection is called Hardware Implemented Fault Injection (HWIFI) and attempts to simulate hardware failures within a system.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] The first experiments in hardware fault involved nothing more than shorting connections on circuit boards and observing the effect on the system (bridging faults).
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] It was used primarily as a test of the dependability of the hardware system.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Later specialised hardware was developed to extend this technique, such as devices to bombard specific areas of a circuit board with heavy radiation.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] It was soon found that faults could be induced by software techniques and that aspects of this technique could be useful for assessing software systems.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Collectively these techniques are known as Software Implemented Fault Injection (SWIFI).
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] SWIFI techniques can be categorized into two types: compile-time injection and runtime injection.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Code mutation produces faults which are very similar to those unintentionally added by programmers.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] A refinement of code mutation is *Code Insertion Fault Injection* which adds code, rather than modifying existing code.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] In this case, pFunc is the perturbation function and it is applied to the return value of the function that has been called introducing a fault into the system.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Runtime injection techniques can use a number of different techniques to insert faults into a system via a trigger.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] These techniques are often based around the debugging facilities provided by computer processor architectures.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Fuzzing is an especially useful form of Black-box testing since the various invalid inputs that are submitted to the software system do not depend on, and are not created based on knowledge of, the details of the code running inside the system.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] This technique is based on a nail bed, necessary to contact the electronics of the products, where a specific test pad has been left free (Design for testability of PCB), and properly inject disturbance signals, in order to see the product's control- reaction arm's reaction if present.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] It's a technique often used to certify and validate reaction to fault in high reliability products, where safety is involved (Military, Medical, Autonomous vehicle).
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Because of the wide complexity a dedicated and complex tools is necessary.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] These parameters create the fault space realm.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] The fault space realm will increase exponentially by increasing system complexity.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Therefore, the traditional fault injection method will not be applicable to use in the modern cyber-physical systems, because they will be so slow, and they will find a small number of faults (less fault coverage).
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Hence, the testers need an efficient algorithm to choose critical faults that have a higher impact on system behavior.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Thus, the main research question is how to find critical faults in the fault space realm which have catastrophic effects on system behavior.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Here are some methods that can aid fault injection to efficiently explore the fault space to reach higher fault coverage in less simulation time.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Although these types of faults can be injected by hand the possibility of introducing an unintended fault is high, so tools exist to parse a program automatically and insert faults.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] A number of SWIFI Tools have been developed and a selection of these tools is given here.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Six commonly used fault injection tools are Ferrari, FTAPE, Doctor, Orchestra, Xception and Grid-FIT.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] In contrast to traditional mutation testing where mutant faults are generated and injected into the code description of the model, application of a series of newly defined mutation operators directly to the model properties rather than to the model code has also been investigated.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Mutant properties that are generated from the initial properties (or test cases) and validated by the model checker should be considered as new properties that have been missed during the initial verification procedure.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Therefore, adding these newly identified properties to the existing list of properties improves the coverage metric of the formal verification and consequently lead to a more reliable design.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] In the testing of operating systems for example, fault injection is often performed by a *driver* (kernel-mode software) that intercepts *system calls* (calls into the kernel) and randomly returning a failure for some of the calls.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] This type of fault injection is useful for testing low-level user-mode software.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] For higher level software, various methods inject faults.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] In managed code, it is common to use instrumentation.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Although fault injection can be undertaken by hand, a number of fault injection tools exist to automate the process of fault injection.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Depending on the complexity of the API for the level where faults are injected, fault injection tests often must be carefully designed to minimize the number of false positives.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Even a well designed fault injection test can sometimes produce situations that are impossible in the normal operation of the software.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] For example, imagine there are two API functions, `Commit` and `PrepareForCommit`, such that alone, each of these functions can possibly fail, but if `PrepareForCommit` is called and succeeds, a subsequent call to `Commit` is guaranteed to succeed.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] Often, it will be infeasible for the fault injection implementation to keep track of enough state to make the guarantee that the API functions make.
[src:fault-injection-defense/fault-injection] In this example, a fault injection test of the above code might hit the assert, whereas this would never happen in normal operation.
[src:fault-injection-defense/hardware-security] A hardware security module (HSM) is a physical computing device that safeguards and manages digital keys for strong authentication and provides cryptoprocessing.
[src:fault-injection-defense/hardware-security] These modules traditionally come in the form of a plug-in card or an external device that attaches directly to a computer or network server.
[src:fault-injection-defense/hardware-security] Some providers in this discipline consider that the key difference between hardware security and software security is that hardware security is implemented using "non-Turing-machine" logic (raw combinatorial logic or simple state machines).
[src:fault-injection-defense/hardware-security] One approach, referred to as "hardsec", uses FPGAs to implement non-Turing-machine security controls as a way of combining the security of hardware with the flexibility of software.
[src:fault-injection-defense/hardware-security] Hardware backdoors are backdoors in hardware.
[src:fault-injection-defense/hardware-security] Conceptionally related, a hardware Trojan (HT) is a malicious modification of electronic system, particularly in the context of integrated circuit.
[src:fault-injection-defense/hardware-security] A physical unclonable function (PUF) is a physical entity that is embodied in a physical structure and is easy to evaluate but hard to predict.
[src:fault-injection-defense/hardware-security] Further, an individual PUF device must be easy to make but practically impossible to duplicate, even given the exact manufacturing process that produced it.
[src:fault-injection-defense/hardware-security] In this respect it is the hardware analog of a one-way function.
[src:fault-injection-defense/hardware-security] The name "physical unclonable function" might be a little misleading as some PUFs are clonable, and most PUFs are noisy and therefore do not achieve the requirements for a function.
[src:fault-injection-defense/hardware-security] Today, PUFs are usually implemented in integrated circuits and are typically used in applications with high security requirements.
[src:fault-injection-defense/hardware-security] Many attacks on sensitive data and resources reported by organizations occur from within the organization itself.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Tamper resistance ranges from simple features like screws with special drives and tamper-evident seals to more complex devices that render themselves inoperable or encrypt all data transmissions between individual chips, use of materials needing special tools and knowledge.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Tamper-resistant devices or features are common on packages to deter package or product tampering or enable its detection.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Anti-tamper devices have one or more components: tamper resistance, tamper detection, tamper response, and tamper evidence.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] In some applications, devices are only tamper-evident rather than tamper-resistant.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Tampering involves the deliberate altering or adulteration of a product, package, or system.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Solutions may involve all phases of product production, packaging, distribution, logistics, sale, and use.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] No single solution can be considered as "tamper-proof".
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Often multiple levels of security need to be addressed to reduce the risk of tampering.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Some devices contain non-standard screws or bolts in an attempt to deter access.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Examples are telephone switching cabinets (which have triangular bolt heads that a hex socket fits), or bolts with 5-sided heads used to secure doors to outdoor electrical distribution transformers.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] A standard Torx screw head can be made in a tamper-resistant form with a pin in the center, which excludes standard Torx drivers.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Various other security screw heads have been devised to discourage casual access to the interior of such devices as consumer electronics.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] This style of tamper resistance is most commonly found in burglar alarms.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Most trip devices (e.g. pressure pads, passive infrared sensors (motion detectors), door switches) use two signal wires that, depending on configuration, are normally open or normally closed.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] The sensors sometimes need power, so to simplify cable runs, multi-core cable is used.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] While 4 cores is normally enough for devices that require power (leaving two spare for those that don't), cable with additional cores can be used.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] These additional cores can be wired into a special so-called "tamper circuit" in the alarm system.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Tamper circuits are monitored by the system to give an alarm if a disturbance to devices or wiring is detected.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Enclosures for devices and control panels may be fitted with anti-tamper switches.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Would-be intruders run the risk of triggering the alarm by attempting to circumvent a given device.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Sensors such as movement detectors, tilt detectors, air-pressure sensors, light sensors, etc., which might be employed in some burglar alarms, might also be used in a bomb to hinder defusing.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Nearly all appliances and accessories can only be opened with the use of a tool.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] This is intended to prevent casual or accidental access to energized or hot parts, or damage to the equipment.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Manufacturers may use tamper-resistant screws, which cannot be unfastened with common tools.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Tamper-resistant screws are used on electrical fittings in many public buildings to reduce tampering or vandalism that may cause a danger to others.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] A user who breaks equipment by modifying it in a way not intended by the manufacturer might deny they did it, in order to claim the warranty or (mainly in the case of PCs) call the helpdesk for help in fixing it.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Tamper-evident seals may be enough to deal with this.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] However, they cannot easily be checked remotely, and many countries have statutory warranty terms that mean manufacturers may still have to service the equipment.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Tamper proof screws will stop most casual users from tampering in the first place.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] In the US, the Magnuson-Moss Warranty Act prevents manufacturers from voiding warranties solely due to tampering.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] A warranty may be dishonored only if the tampering actually affected the part that has failed, and could have caused the failure.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Tamper-resistant microprocessors are used to store and process private or sensitive information, such as private keys or electronic money credit.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] To prevent an attacker from retrieving or modifying the information, the chips are designed so that the information is not accessible through external means and can be accessed only by the embedded software, which should contain the appropriate security measures.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Examples of tamper-resistant chips include all secure cryptoprocessors, such as the IBM 4758 and chips used in smartcards, as well as the Clipper chip.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Tamper-resistant chips may be designed to zeroise their sensitive data (especially cryptographic keys) if they detect penetration of their security encapsulation or out-of-specification environmental parameters.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] A chip may even be rated for "cold zeroisation", the ability to zeroise itself even after its power supply has been crippled.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] In addition, the custom-made encapsulation methods used for chips used in some cryptographic products may be designed in such a manner that they are internally pre-stressed, so the chip will fracture if interfered with.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Nevertheless, the fact that an attacker may have the device in their possession for as long as they like, and perhaps obtain numerous other samples for testing and practice, means that it is impossible to totally eliminate tampering by a sufficiently motivated opponent.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Because of this, one of the most important elements in protecting a system is overall system design.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] In particular, tamper-resistant systems should "fail gracefully" by ensuring that compromise of one device does not compromise the entire system.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] In this manner, the attacker can be practically restricted to attacks that cost more than the expected return from compromising a single device.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Since the most sophisticated attacks have been estimated to cost several hundred thousand dollars to carry out, carefully designed systems may be invulnerable in practice.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] In the United States, purchasing specifications require anti-tamper (AT) features on military electronic systems.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Tamper resistance finds application in smart cards, set-top boxes and other devices that use digital rights management (DRM).
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] In this case, the issue is not about stopping the user from breaking the equipment or hurting themselves, but about either stopping them from extracting codes, or acquiring and saving the decoded bitstream.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] This is usually done by having many subsystem features buried within each chip (so that internal signals and states are inaccessible) and by making sure the buses between chips are encrypted.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] DRM mechanisms also use certificates and asymmetric key cryptography in many cases.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] In all such cases, tamper resistance means not allowing the device user access to the valid device certificates or public-private keys of the device.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] The process of making software robust against tampering attacks is referred to as "software anti-tamper".
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Resistance to tampering can be built in or added to packaging.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] Software is also said to be tamper-resistant when it contains measures to make reverse engineering harder, or to prevent a user from modifying it against the manufacturer's wishes (such as removing a restriction on how it can be used).
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] One commonly used method is code obfuscation.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] However, effective tamper resistance in software is much harder than in hardware, as the software environment can be manipulated to near-arbitrary extent by the use of emulation.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] If implemented, trusted computing would make software tampering of protected programs at least as difficult as hardware tampering, as the user would have to hack the trust chip to give false certifications in order to bypass remote attestation and sealed storage.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] However, the current specification makes it clear that the chip is not expected to be tamper-proof against any reasonably sophisticated physical attack; that is, it is not intended to be as secure as a tamper-resistant device.
[src:fault-injection-defense/tamper-resistance] That has the side effect that software maintenance gets more complex because software updates need to be validated, and errors in the upgrade process may lead to a false-positive triggering of the protection mechanism.
